@mjlbach You should be able to reproduce it using the following Rust file:

```rust
fn main() {
    println!(
        "{}",
        42
    );
}
```

Open this file in two vertical splits. In the right split, move the cursor to `4`. In the left split, move the cursor to the `p` in `println!`. So like this:

```
fn main() {       |  fn main() {
    [p]rintln!(   |      println!(
        "{}",     |          "{}",
        42        |          [4]2
    );            |      );
}                 |  }
```

Where `[X]` it the block/visual cursor position.

Then format the file. If you move the cursor back to the right split, it's moved to the start of the file; instead of being located at `4`. With my extmarks hack it sort of works but not always (e.g. in this case the cursor ends up at `)` and not `4`, but most of the time it's where I would expect it).
